   529	
   530	## YAML State Machine Format Specification
   531	
   532	This section defines the formal structure of YAML state machine configuration files. All state machines must conform to this specification.
   533	
   534	### Root-Level Fields
   535	
   536	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   537	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   538	| `name` | string | Yes | Unique identifier for the state machine |
   539	| `models` | string array | No | Declared model profile identifiers available to states in this machine |
   540	| `version` | string | Yes | Semantic version of the state machine definition |
   541	| `states` | object | Yes | Map of state names to state definitions |
   542	| `transitions` | array | Yes | List of allowed state transitions |
   543	| `callbacks` | object | No | Platform-specific callback mappings |
   544	| `error_handling` | object | No | Error handling and recovery configuration |
   545	
   546	### State Definition
   547	
   548	Each state is defined as a key-value pair in the `states` object:
   549	
   550	```yaml
   551	states:
   552	  <state-name>:
   553	    description: <string>       # Required: Human-readable description of the state
   554	    instructions: <string>      # Optional: Agent-facing instructions for work in this state
   555	    final: <boolean>            # Optional: true if this is a terminal state (no outgoing transitions)
   556	    gating: <boolean>           # Optional: true if no autonomous (agent/engine) transitions are allowed out
   557	    visits: <integer>           # Optional: maximum number of visits permitted for this state
   558	    target: <string>            # Optional: inline execution target selector
   559	    all_targets: [<string>]     # Optional: run this state once per listed target
   560	    all_models: [<string>]      # Optional: list of declared model profiles; run this state once per listed model
   561	    model: <string>             # Optional: one declared model profile allowed for this state
   562	    agent: <string>             # Optional: coding agent id for this state (see Agents Specification)
   563	    agent_mode: <string>        # Optional: named mode on the resolved agent
   564	    agent_timeout: <duration>   # Optional: max time an agent may work in this state (e.g., "30m")
   565	    program: <string|object>    # Optional: deterministic program to execute (see Program States Specification)
   566	    program_timeout: <duration> # Optional: max time a program may run in this state (e.g., "10m")
   567	    mcp_servers: [<string|object>]  # Optional: MCP servers attached to the agent for this state
   568	    skills: [<string|object>]       # Optional: agent skills enabled for this state
   569	```
   570	
   571	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   572	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   573	| `description` | string | Yes | Human-readable explanation of what this state represents |
   574	| `instructions` | string | No | Agent-facing guidance for work in this state. Supports [template variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality) resolved by `rhei next` at output time. |
   575	| `personality` | string | No | Optional role framing printed alongside the next claimed task when this state is active. Supports [template variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality). |
   576	| `final` | boolean | No | Marks this as a terminal state. Tasks in final states cannot transition further |
   577	| `gating` | boolean | No | Marks this as a gating state. When `true`, autonomous commands (`rhei next`, `rhei complete`, engine-triggered transitions) must not transition out of this state. Only explicit human-initiated transitions (`rhei transition` with `triggeredBy: 'user'`) are allowed. |
   578	| `visits` | integer | No | Maximum number of visits permitted for this state before the loop budget is exhausted |
   579	| `target` | string | No | Inline execution target selector. Preferred over the legacy `model` + `agent` split for new workflows. |
   580	| `all_targets` | string array | No | Explicit list of execution target selectors; the state runs once for each listed target. Preferred over `all_models` for new fanout workflows. |
   581	| `all_models` | string array | No | Explicit list of declared model profile identifiers; the state runs once for each listed model |
   582	| `model` | string | No | Restricts the state to one model profile declared in the machine-level `models` list |
   583	| `agent` | string | No | Coding agent id for this state. Must resolve against the merged `agents` registry (built-ins + `settings.json`). Inline agent objects are not accepted — declare custom agents in `agents.<id>` first. See [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md). |
   584	| `agent_mode` | string | No | Named flag set from the resolved agent's `modes` map (e.g., `yolo`, `safe`). See [Agents Specification — Modes](rhei-agents.spec.md#modes). |
   585	| `agent_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time an agent may work in this state (e.g., `30m`, `1h`). When exceeded, `rhei run` kills the agent and fires a timeout transition if one is declared. |
   586	| `program` | string or object | No | Deterministic program command for this state. String form runs via shell. Object form specifies `command`, `env`, `working_directory`. Mutually exclusive with `agent`. See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md). |
   587	| `program_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time a program may run in this state (e.g., `10m`, `1h`). Same timeout mechanism as `agent_timeout`. |
   588	| `inputs` | artifact array | No | Required file artifacts that must exist before entering or working this state |
   589	| `outputs` | artifact array | No | Required file artifacts that must exist before leaving this state |
   590	| `mcp_servers` | array | No | MCP server entries (ids or inline definitions) attached to the agent subprocess. Individual entries may be marked `optional: true`. Mutually exclusive with `gating: true` and `program:`. See [States Specification — MCP Servers and Skills](rhei-states.spec.md#mcp-servers-and-skills). |
   591	| `skills` | array | No | Skill entries enabled for the agent in this state. Same shape and exclusions as `mcp_servers`. |
   592	
   593	Model selection rules:
   594	- The machine-level `models` list is optional. When omitted, states are not model-constrained.
   595	- A state may set `target: <selector>` or `all_targets: [<selector>, ...]` as
   596	  an inline execution selector.
   597	- `target` and `all_targets` are mutually exclusive.
   598	- `target` / `all_targets` must not be combined with `model`, `all_models`,
   599	  `agent`, or `agent_mode`.
   600	- Target selectors must use one of these forms:
   601	  `<agent>:<model>`, `<agent>[<mode>]:<model>`,
   602	  `<agent>:<provider>:<model>`, or
   603	  `<agent>[<mode>]:<provider>:<model>`.
   604	- `all_targets`, when present, must be a non-empty list of unique selectors.
   605	- In a target selector, `<agent>` must resolve against the merged `agents`
   606	  registry.
   607	- In a target selector, `<mode>`, when present, must resolve against the
   608	  selected agent's declared modes.
   609	- In a target selector, `<provider>`, when present, must be non-empty.
   610	- In a target selector, `<model>` must be non-empty.
   611	- A state may set `all_models: [<name>, ...]` or `model: <name>`, but not both.
   612	- `model` must reference a value declared in the machine-level `models` list.
   613	- `all_models`, when present, must be a non-empty list of unique values declared in the machine-level `models` list.
   614	- A state with `all_models` is executed once per listed model.
   615	- A state with `all_targets` is executed once per listed target.
   616	- `visits` may be combined with either `all_models` or `model`.
   617	- `visits` may also be combined with either `all_targets` or `target`.
   618	- `visits`, when present, must be an integer greater than or equal to `1`.
   619	- `inputs` and `outputs`, when present, must be arrays of unique artifact definitions keyed by `name`.
   620	- Artifact `path` values are execution-root-relative templates; see [main spec — State Artifact Contracts](../rhei.spec.md#10-state-artifact-contracts) for the definition of execution root. After expansion, they must remain within that root.
   621	
   622	Artifact definition:
   623	
   624	```yaml
   625	states:
   626	  review:
   627	    outputs:
   628	      - name: findings
   629	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}.md
   630	        description: Concrete review findings for the task
   631	```
   632	
   633	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   634	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   635	| `name` | string | Yes | Stable identifier for the artifact within that state |
   636	| `path` | string | Yes | Workspace-relative file path template |
   637	| `description` | string | No | Human-readable explanation of the artifact |
   638	
   639	Supported template variables:
   640	
   641	- `{task_id}` - current task id
   642	- `{state}` - canonical unsuffixed state name
   643	- `{visit_count}` - current visit number for counted-loop states (only available when the state declares `visits`)
   644	- `{target}` - current execution target selector (only available when the state declares `target` or `all_targets`)
   645	- `{target.slug}` - filesystem-safe slug for the current target selector
   646	- `{agent}` - current agent id
   647	- `{agent.mode}` - current agent mode, if any
   648	- `{model}` - current model identifier (available when the state declares `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`)
   649	- `{model.provider}` - current model provider id
   650	- `{model.name}` - current provider model name
   651	
   652	### Counted Loops
   653	
   654	This section describes the runtime semantics of the `visits` field, also
   655	called *counted visits* in the main plan specification and the states
   656	specification. The three terms — `visits`, *counted visits*, and *counted
   657	loops* — refer to the same mechanism.
   658	
   659	`visits` is a state-level loop budget. It is used when a workflow intentionally cycles through the same state multiple times before taking a non-loop exit.
   660	

